{"key":"post-8786921","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8786921</id>\n<content>Casing is optional with manure, coir, compost and straw substrates, but a well maintained casing layer will generally improve results.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The 'old' way was to apply the casing layer right after spawning colonized grains to manure.&amp;nbsp; Now, it's generally preferred to wait until the substrate has colonized before adding the casing.&amp;nbsp; However, either way will work.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Personally, I prefer to fruit manure substrates uncased with a layer of wax paper over the top to maintain humidity right at the surface where primordia form.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8786957</next>\n<prev>8786846</prev>\n<first>8786846</first>\n<last>8786966</last>\n<when>1219003018</when>\n<utime>08/17/08 10:56 PM</utime>\n</post>"}